Project Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Definition of Problem Statement and Objectives

Business Context

The advent of e-news, or electronic news, portals has offered us a great opportunity to quickly get updates on the day-to-day events occurring globally. The information on these portals is retrieved electronically from online databases, processed using a variety of software, and then transmitted to the users. There are multiple advantages of transmitting new electronically, like faster access to the content and the ability to utilize different technologies such as audio, graphics, video, and other interactive elements that are either not being used or aren’t common yet in traditional newspapers.

E-news Express, an online news portal, aims to expand its business by acquiring new subscribers. With every visitor to the website taking certain actions based on their interest, the company plans to analyze these actions to understand user interests and determine how to drive better engagement. The executives at E-news Express are of the opinion that there has been a decline in new monthly subscribers compared to the past year because the current webpage is not designed well enough in terms of the outline & recommended content to keep customers engaged long enough to make a decision to subscribe.

  1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than on the existing landing page?
  2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?
  3. Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?
  4. Is the time spent on the new page the same for the different language users?

[Companies often analyze user responses to two variants of a product to decide which of the two variants is more effective. This experimental technique, known as A/B testing, is used to determine whether a new feature attracts users based on a chosen metric.] Objective

The design team of the company has researched and created a new landing page that has a new outline & more relevant content shown compared to the old page. In order to test the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers, the Data Science team conducted an experiment by randomly selecting 100 users and dividing them equally into two groups. The existing landing page was served to the first group (control group) and the news landing page to the second group (treatment group). Data regarding the interaction of users in both groups with the two versions of the landing page was collected. Being a data scientist in E-news Express, you have been asked to explore the data and perform a statistical analysis (at a significance level of 5%) to determine the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers for the news portal by answering the following questions:

  1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than on the existing landing page?
  2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?
  3. Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?
  4. Is the time spent on the new page the same for the different language users?

Data Dictionary

The data contains information regarding the interaction of users in both groups with the two versions of the landing page.

user_id - Unique user ID of the person visiting the website
group - Whether the user belongs to the first group (control) or the second group (treatment)
landing_page - Whether the landing page is new or old
time_spent_on_the_page - Time (in minutes) spent by the user on the landing page
converted - Whether the user gets converted to a subscriber of the news portal or not
language_preferred - Language chosen by the user to view the landing page

1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page?¶

Displaying Visual Analysis

In [ ]:
# visual analysis of the time spent on the new page and the time spent on the old page
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.boxplot(x = 'landing_page', y = 'time_spent_on_the_page', data = data)
plt.show()

The visual analysis of the boxplot of time spent on the page versus to the landing indictaes that generally the duration of time spent on the page was higher on the new page and lower on the old page. Hence a higher median (about 6 minutes) was recorded for the new page compared to the old page (just above 4 minutes).

there was a high variance on the time spent on the old page compared to the new page which had a relatively lower variance. This means that comparatively there were more spread in the time spent on the old page.

The spread of time spent on the new page was less spread leading to a less variance in the data.

The changes made on the new page resulted in an increase on the mean time spent on the page upon landing. This information can be used by the business to understand some of the factors affecting increase on time spent on the page which could drive business by increasing subscription rates.

Defining the null and alternate hypotheses

H0: μ1​=μ2​

H1: 𝜇1≠𝜇2

Null Hypothesis (H0): μ1=μ2 The mean time spent on the new page is equal to the mean time spent on the old page. That is; the population means of the control/old and treatment/new groups are equal.

Alternative Hypothesis (H1): μ1≠𝜇2 [not equal] The mean time spent on the new page is different from the mean time spent on the old page. The time spent on the old page is not equal to time spent on the new page. That is the population mean of the control/old group is less than the population mean of the treatment/new group.

Selecting appropriate test

T test for independent sample is the appropriate test as this is a one-tailed test concerning two population means from two independent populations with unknown population standard deviations.

Deciding the significance level

0.05

Collecting and preparing subsetted data for new and old landing page users

In [ ]:
# create subsetted data frame for new landing page users
time_spent_new = data[data['landing_page'] == 'new']['time_spent_on_the_page']

# create subsetted data frame for old landing page users
time_spent_old = data[data['landing_page'] == 'old']['time_spent_on_the_page']

Finding the mean and standard deviations

In [ ]:
# find the sample means and sample standard deviations for the two samples

print('The sample mean of the time spent on the new page is:', round(time_spent_new.mean()))
print('The sample mean of the time spent on the old page is:', round(time_spent_old.mean()))
print('The sample standard deviation of the time spent on the new page is:', round(time_spent_new.std(),2))
print('The sample standard deviation of the time spent on the old page is:', round(time_spent_old.std(),2))

The sample mean of the time spent on the new page is: 6
The sample mean of the time spent on the old page is: 5
The sample standard deviation of the time spent on the new page is: 1.82
The sample standard deviation of the time spent on the old page is: 2.58

A two-sample t-test was conducted to compare the mean time spent on the new page (mean = 6) with the mean time spent on the old page (mean = 5).

The mean time spent on the new page is 6 minutes with a standard deviation of 1.82 minutes. The mean time spent on the old page was 5 minutes with a standard deviation of 2.58 minutes. Therefore the population standard deviations can be assumed to be different.

Calculating the p-value

In [ ]:
# complete the code to import the required function
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
In [ ]:
# write the code to calculate the p-value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(time_spent_new, time_spent_old, equal_var = False, alternative = 'greater')
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.0001392381225166549

The p-value is 0.000139 as the calculated p-value is 0.00013920.0001392, which is less than the common significance level of 0.050.05.

Comparing the p-value with level of significance

In [ ]:
# print the conclusion based on p-value
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.0001392381225166549 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

As the p-value (~0.0001) is less than the level of significance (0.05), we can reject the null hypothesis. Thus based on the small p-value, we reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis (H1H1​).

Therefore, there is sufficient evidence to suggest that the mean time spent on the new page is different from the mean time spent on the old page.

Hence, we do have enough evidence to support the claim that the time taken on the old page is similar to time taken on the new page.

Drawing inference

Based on the small p-value, we reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis.

As the p-value (0.00014) is less than the level of significance (0.05), we can reject the null hypothesis. That is, we do not have enough evidence to support the claim that the time taken on the old page is similar to time taken on the new page.

Hence, we do not have enough evidence to reject the alternate hypothesis that states that the time spent on the new page and old page is different. This means that there is sufficient evidence to suggest that the mean time spent on the new page is different from the mean time spent on the old page.

In summary, the observed data provide strong evidence to conclude that there is a significant difference in the mean times spent on the new and old pages.

This findings would be improtant to the sales department of the business as there is enough evidence to suggest that the means of the new and old pages are different with the new pages having increased the time spent on the page by the clients. The information can be used to improve business especially if the business is looking to increase the time spent on the pages.

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

Displaying visual analysis of the landing page and converted

In [ ]:

Generally, the conversion rations for both the old and new landing pages were different. The new page recorded more conversions and less non-conversions. The old page landing page recorded less conversions (about 40%) and more non-conversions (almost 60%).

A greater proportion of landings on the new page (about 65%) resulted into conversion to subscription. In fact the proportion of convertions on the new page were greater than the non-conversions (about 35%).

This information could be used to add credence to the changes implemented on the page and can increase subscriptions and the business in general.

Defining the null and alternate hypotheses

𝐻0 : 𝜇1≤𝜇

𝐻𝑎 : 𝜇1>𝜇

The null hypothesis states that; The conversion rate for the new page is less than or equal to the conversion rate for the old page.

Alternative Hypothesis states that; The conversion rate for the new page is greater than the conversion rate for the old page.

Determining the appropriate test

This is a one-tailed test concerning two population proportions from two independent populations. Based on this information, the appropriate test is one sided Z test for proportions.

Display the significance level

In [ ]:
α = 0.05

The level of significance is pegged at 0.05 which is 95% confidence level

Collecting and preparing data

In [ ]:
# calculate the number of converted users in the treatment group
new_converted = data[data['group'] == 'treatment']['converted'].value_counts()['yes']

# calculate the number of converted users in the control group
old_converted = data[data['group'] == 'control']['converted'].value_counts()['yes']

# total number of users in the control group
n_control = data.group.value_counts()['control']

# total number of users in the treatment group
n_treatment = data.group.value_counts()['treatment']

print('The numbers of users served the new and old pages are {0} and {1} respectively'.format(n_control, n_treatment ))

The numbers of users served the new and old pages are 50 and 50 respectively

Computing the test statistic and p-value

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

# Assuming you have a DataFrame named 'data' containing relevant columns
# 'converted' indicates whether the user gets converted (yes or no)
# 'landing_page' indicates whether the landing page is old or new

# Create a contingency table
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(data['converted'], data['landing_page'])

# Extract counts for the old and new landing pages
converted_old = contingency_table['old']['yes']
converted_new = contingency_table['new']['yes']

# Extract total counts for the old and new landing pages
n_old = contingency_table['old'].sum()
n_new = contingency_table['new'].sum()

# Perform z-test for proportions
stat, p_value = proportions_ztest([converted_old, converted_new], [n_old, n_new], alternative='larger')

# Output the results
print(f'Z-statistic: {stat:.4f}')
print(f'P-value: {p_value:.4f}')

Z-statistic: -2.4077
P-value: 0.9920

Given that; Z-statistic: -2.4077 and P-value: 0.9920

The Z-statistic is negative, indicating that the observed proportion for the new page is lower than the observed proportion for the old page.

The p-value is 0.9920, which is significantly greater than the common significance level of 0.05.

Comparing the p-value and level of significance

In [ ]:
# Check if the p-value is less than the significance level (e.g., 0.05)
if p_value < 0.05:
    print('Reject the null hypothesis: The conversion rate for the new page is greater than the old page.')
else:
    print('Fail to reject the null hypothesis: There is no significant difference in conversion rates.')

Fail to reject the null hypothesis: There is no significant difference in conversion rates.

Based on the p-value, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Inference

There is insufficient evidence to conclude that the conversion rate for the new page is greater than the conversion rate for the old page.

The observed data do not provide significant support for the alternative hypothesis, suggesting that any observed difference in conversion rates is likely due to random variation.

In summary, the results do not support the claim that the new page has a higher conversion rate than the old page based on the given significance level.

Inference

As the p-value (0.0000000009) is less than the level of significance (0.05), we can reject the null hypothesis. Hence, we do have enough evidence to support the alternative hypothesis which claims that the conversion rate on the new page is greater than that on the old page. Instead we can not reject the ascertion that the conversion on the new page is greater than on the old page

The changes on the new page is of significance to the business as the changes on the new page have resulted in increase in clients landing on the new page converting to subcription as compared to the those landing on the old page and therefore the change will increse or drive business positively.

Defining the null and alternate hypotheses

H0: (Null Hypothesis): Conversion status and preferred language Language are independent.

H1 (Alternative Hypothesis): Conversion status and preferred language are dependent or related.

To test whether the conversion status and preferred language are independent or related, you can set up the following null and alternative hypotheses for a test of independence:

The null hypothesis states that: The conversion status and preferred language are independent.

The alternative states that the converted satus and preferred language are dependent or related

Selecting the appropriate test

Chi-square test for independence

Displaying the significance level

p=0.05

One-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) test

p=0.05

Calculating the p-value

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# Assuming you have created time_spent_English, time_spent_French, and time_spent_Spanish data frames

# Perform t-test for English vs. French
t_stat_ef, p_value_ef = ttest_ind(time_spent_English, time_spent_French)

# Perform t-test for English vs. Spanish
t_stat_es, p_value_es = ttest_ind(time_spent_English, time_spent_Spanish)

# Perform t-test for French vs. Spanish
t_stat_fs, p_value_fs = ttest_ind(time_spent_French, time_spent_Spanish)

# Print the p-values
print('P-value for English vs. French:', p_value_ef)
print('P-value for English vs. Spanish:', p_value_es)
print('P-value for French vs. Spanish:', p_value_fs)

P-value for English vs. French: 0.6144183126667917
P-value for English vs. Spanish: 0.47502128661672227
P-value for French vs. Spanish: 0.8263991691376782

The p-values obtained from the t-tests for the pairwise comparisons of time spent on the new page for different language users are as follows:

P-value for English vs. French: 0.6144183126667917 P-value for English vs. Spanish: 0.47502128661672227 P-value for French vs. Spanish: 0.8263991691376782

English vs. French: P-value: 0.6144 Conclusion: Fail to reject the null hypothesis. Interpretation: There is no significant difference in the mean time spent on the new page between English and French language users.

English vs. Spanish: P-value: 0.4750 Conclusion: Fail to reject the null hypothesis. Interpretation: There is no significant difference in the mean time spent on the new page between English and Spanish language users.

French vs. Spanish: P-value: 0.8264 Conclusion: Fail to reject the null hypothesis. Interpretation: There is no significant difference in the mean time spent on the new page between French and Spanish language users.

In summary, based on the provided p-values, there is insufficient evidence to suggest that there are significant differences in the mean time spent on the new page among English, French, and Spanish language users.

Conclusion: Fail to Reject the Null Hypothesis

This means there is insufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis based on the observed data. Therefore, the observed findings are not statistically significant at 0.05 and we do not have enough evidence to support alternative hypothesis.

So the null hypotheis which indicates no effect or difference is consistent with the data

With a p-value of 0.2129 greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This suggests that, based on the available evidence, there is not enough support to claim a statistically significant effect or difference as per the data set and hypothesis.

It's important to note that failing to reject the null hypothesis does not prove the null hypothesis is true, it simply means that the data does not provide enough evidence to reject it.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

CONCLUSIONS

There is insufficient evidence to suggest a significant relationship between conversion status and preferred language at the 0.05 significance level. The p-value of 0.2129 indicates that any observed association between conversion status and preferred language in the sample is likely due to random chance. Therefore, based on the data, we do not have statistical grounds to conclude that conversion status and preferred language are significantly related.

For the new landing page effectiveness: The new landing page design has been shown to significantly increase the time spent on the page compared to the old page. Implementing the new landing page design is likely to result in increased user engagement and interaction with the platform.

Conversion rate for new page: The conversion rate for the new page is not significantly greater than the conversion rate for the old page. Further optimization or testing may be needed to enhance the new page's conversion rate. The business could onsider exploring alternative designs or features to improve user conversion.

Time spent on new pPage by language Users: There is no significant difference in the time spent on the new page among users with different language preferences. While time spent is similar across language groups, ongoing monitoring and user feedback may help identify opportunities for language-specific content improvements.

Conversion status and preferred language: There is no significant relationship between conversion status and preferred language. Conversion status appears to be independent of the preferred language. There will be need to focus on other factors influencing conversion and tailor marketing strategies accordingly.

In summary, the business can proceed with implementing the new landing page design for its positive impact on user engagement. For conversion rates, further optimization efforts are recommended. Additionally, while language preferences do not significantly impact time spent or conversion, continued monitoring and user feedback are crucial for providing a tailored and user-friendly experience.

BUSINESS RECOMMENDATIONS

The business recommendations will depend on the specific oerational context and goals of the company. However, some general recommendations based on the hypotheses tests conducted:

New landing page effectiveness: Recommendation: Given the statistical evidence supporting that the new landing page is effective in increasing the time spent on the page, the company should consider implementing the new design on a larger scale. Action: Roll out the new landing page design to a broader audience and monitor key metrics to ensure the positive impact persists.

Conversion rate for new page: Recommendation: With the evidence suggesting that the conversion rate for the new page is not significantly greater than the old page, the business could consider further optimization or testing alternative designs to enhance conversion. Action: The business to conduct more A/B testing with variations of the new page or implement additional features to improve conversion rates.

Time spent on new page by language users: Recommendation: Since the p-values for the pairwise comparisons of time spent on the new page for different language users are all greater than 0.05, there is no significant difference. However, the business could monitor user engagement and preferences to tailor content for diverse language groups. Action: Continue tracking user behavior and preferences. Consider implementing language-specific content or features if user feedback supports it.

Conversion status and preferred language: Recommendation: As the p-value for the chi-squared test is greater than 0.05, indicating no significant relationship between conversion status and preferred language, focus should be on other factors influencing conversion. Action: Explore additional factors influencing conversion and consider tailoring marketing strategies based on those factors.

Ongoing monitoring and evaluation will be required to ensure that changes implemented yield the desired results.
